    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-04-10T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-04-10T23:00:00-05:00" n="480"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d480">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">721.23/2186: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dearing</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-04-10T23:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 10, 1934—11 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 10—3:07 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>45. 1. Subsequent to Cabinet meeting Foreign Minister informed me yesterday
                    notification given by Governor Canal Zone under orders of Department of State
                    repair facilities at Panama would be denied to Peruvian naval vessel <hi
                        rend="italic">Bologne</hi> [<hi rend="italic">si</hi>] which is much
                    resented by President, Minister of Marine, and other Cabinet members. I assured
                    Minister any measures taken could not have been directed against Perú and would
                    certainly be applied with absolute impartiality. Freyre has been instructed to
                    make representations to the Department.</p>
                <pb facs="0449" n="379" xml:id="pg_379"/>
                <p>2. Press reports of enlistment of American aviators with Colombians have also
                    caused a very bad impression the Minister informed me.</p>
                <p>3. He is undoubtedly misinformed and accurate information is lacking. I set
                    before him our position as outlined in Department’s 423, December 10, 1932,<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d480fn2">
                        <ref target="frus1932v05#pg_962">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1932, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, p. 962</ref>.</note> but he is inclined to
                    make capital of statements in Embassy’s note 281, July 12th,<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d480fn3">
                        <ref target="frus1932v05#pg_955">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, p. 955</ref>.</note> enclosure 1, with
                    Embassy’s despatch 1938 of July 18, 1932,<note n="4" xml:id="d480fn4">
                        <ref target="frus1932v05#pg_950">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, p. 950</ref>.</note> as showing
                    inconsistency. I assured him again of our absolute impartiality and cited case
                    of American aviators in Rif several years ago.<note n="5" xml:id="d480fn5">See
                            <ref target="frus1925v02#pg_606">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, 1925, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>,
                            pp. 606</ref> ff.</note>
                </p>
                <p>4. There can be no doubt the Government here feels we are showing partiality to
                    Colombia, an impression I am endeavoring to remove as well as I am able, but
                    being in the wrong this Government will inevitably misinterpret many things.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dearing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
